SIMPLE: jealousy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Jealousy
<hw>Jeal"ous*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Jealousies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[ F. <ets>jalousie</ets>.
See <er>Jealous</er>, and cf. <er>Jalousie</er>.]</ety> <def>The quality
of being jealous; earnest concern or solicitude; painful apprehension of
rivalship in cases directly affecting one's happiness; painful suspicion
of the faithfulness of husband, wife, or lover.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I was jealous for <qex>jealousy.</qex></q> <rj><qau>Zech. viii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Jealousy is the</qex> . . . apprehension of superiority.</q>
<rj><qau>Shenstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whoever had qualities to alarm our <qex>jealousy</qex>, had
excellence to deserve our fondness.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Jeames</ent>⟦br⟧
